{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. --> | image = | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | pseudonym = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = Tuskegee, Alabama | death_date = | death_place = | resting_place = | occupation = Professor of Criminology and Criminal Justice Administration | language = English | nationality = | ethnicity = | citizenship = | education = PhD in Criminology | alma_mater = Rutgers University: The Graduate School of Criminal Justice | period = | genre = Criminology/Criminal Justice | subject = | movement = | notableworks = ''Continuing The War Against Domestic Violence'' (2014) | spouse = | partner = | children = | relatives = | influences = | influenced = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | website = | portaldisp = }}
'''Lee E. Ross''' is an [[African-American]] [[criminology|criminologist]] and author of articles and books that address issues of [[domestic violence]] and topics related to race, crime, and justice.
==Life== Ross was born in [[Tuskegee, Alabama]], but his parents eventually relocated to [[Hempstead, New York]]. Upon graduating [[Hempstead High School (New York)|Hempstead High School]], he attended [[Niagara University]] in [[Niagara Falls, New York]]. There, he earned a bachelor's degree in [[criminal justice]] before receiving the Patricia Roberts Harris Fellowship to pursue graduate studies at [[Rutgers University]] where he earned his masters and doctorate in criminology. Ross also spent seven years as a federal law enforcement officer with the [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement|United States Customs Service]]. He has held various academic positions, including teaching at the [[University of Wisconsin–Milwaukee]] and the [[University of Wisconsin-Parkside]] (where he served as Department Chair) prior to his current position at the [[University of Central Florida]].
Ross is editor of ''Continuing the War Against Domestic Violence'', 2nd Edition. He is a member of the Academy of Criminal Justice Sciences and the European Society of Criminology. He has received academic awards for teaching excellence and research, including the COHPA Research Fellow award and the Outstanding Mentor of the Year Award from the Academy of Criminal Justice Sciences.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cohpa.ucf.edu/research/fellows/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141019154528/http://www.cohpa.ucf.edu/research/fellows/ |archivedate=2014-10-19 |df= }}</ref> In 1998, his book ''African-American Criminologists, 1970-1996: An Annotated Bibliography'' was the first of it kind to document the scholarly contributions of African-American criminologists to the field of criminal justice, and was described as "the most complete index to the work of Black criminologists" by [[Katheryn Russell-Brown]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Race and Crime: An Annotated Bibliography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2iF-q26wKBEC|year=2000|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-31033-1|page=X}}</ref>
==Selected bibliography== *Ross, L.E. (2014). ''[https://www.amazon.com/Continuing-Against-Domestic-Violence-Second/dp/1482229102/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1414030906&sr=1-1 Continuing the War Against Domestic Violence]''. Boca Raton, FL: CRC Press. * Ross, L.E. and Leslie, T. (2104). Criminal Justice Practitioner Attitudes Toward Domestic Violence: Another Day in Paradise, Law Enforcement Executive Forum, 14, 3:18-31. * Ross, Lee E. (2014). The Prison Industrial Complex., In B. Arrigo, (Ed). Encyclopedia of Criminal Justice Ethics, Thousand Oaks, CA: Sage Publications. * Ross, Lee E. (2013). [http://trace.tennessee.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1041&context=catalyst Religion and Intimate Partner Violence: A Double-Edge Sword.] The Catalyst: A Social Justice Forum. 2, 3:3-12. * Ross, Lee E. (2010). [http://knowledge.sagepub.com/view/hdbk_criminologicaltheory/n21.xml A Vision of Race, Crime, and Justice through the Lens of Critical Race Theory.] In E. McLaughlin and T. Newburn (Eds.), The Sage Handbook of Criminological Theory. London: Sage Publications. (pp.&nbsp;391–409). * Ross, Lee E. (2008). [https://www.ncjrs.gov/App/publications/abstract.aspx?ID=244983 Criminal Justice Pioneers: A content Analysis of Biographical Data.] Journal of Criminal Justice, 36, 2:182-189. * Ross, Lee E. (2007). Consequences of Mandatory Arrest Policies: Comments, Questions, and Concerns, Law Enforcement Executive Forum. 7, 5:73-85. * Ross, L. E. & Elechi, O. (2002). [http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.1080/10511250200085491 Student Attitudes Towards Internship Experience: From Theory and Practice], Journal of Criminal Justice Education.13 (2): 297-312. * Palermo, G. & Ross, L. E. (1999). Mass Murder, Suicide, and Moral Development: Can we Separate the Adults from the Juveniles? International Journal of Offender Therapy and Comparative Criminology. 43(1), 8-20 * Ross, Lee E., (1998) African American Criminologists: 1970-1996, Westport: Greenwood Publications. * Ross, L. E. & Edwards, W. J. (1998). Publishing Among African American Criminologists: A Devaluing Experience? Journal of Criminal Justice vol. 26(1): 29-40. * Ross, Lee E. 1994. Religion and Deviance: Exploring the Impact of Social Control Elements, Sociological Spectrum, 14 (1): 65-86 * Ross, Lee E. 1992. Blacks, Self-Esteem, and Delinquency: It's Time for a New Approach, Justice Quarterly 9(4): 609-24. 1992.
