'''Memons in South Africa''' form a prosperous [[Muslim]] subgroup in that country's [[Indians in South Africa|Indian]] community and are largely descended from [[Kathiawadi Memon|Memons from Kathiawar]] who immigrated from [[Undivided India|India]] in the late 19th century/early 20th century.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} Villages and towns that South African Memons originated from include [[Porbander]], [[Bhanvad]], [[Ranavav]] and [[Jodiya]].

Memons played a major role in the promotion of [[Islam in South Africa]], and there have been rivalries for the management of local mosques between Memons and [[Surti Muslims|Surtis]], who are Gujarati-speaking Sunni Muslims.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} This is primarily due to the different 'Maslak' (path) [[Deobandi]] mainly Surti, and [[Barelvi]] mainly Memon, although these are far less prominent than they were in the past.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}

Although the [[Memoni language]] is not widely spoken by younger Memons in South Africa, South African Memons continue to maintain a strong (although slowly eroding) Memon identity. Already, few younger Memons are aware of the towns where their ancestors came from.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} Although the early Memons practiced [[endogamy]] (marrying within their social group, including ancestral village), intermarriage between Memon groups and other [[Sunni Muslims]] is now widely accepted, mirroring a similar integration among Gujarati Hindu groups from Surat and Shauarashtra.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kendra.org.za/samachar/Samachar%20Edition%2020_MAIL.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-09-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130807033709/http://kendra.org.za/samachar/Samachar%20Edition%2020_MAIL.pdf |archivedate=2013-08-07 |df= }}</ref>

Memon organisations in South Africa include the [[Memon Association of South Africa]] (formerly the 'Memon Association of the Transvaal'), the [http://www.samemonfoundation.org Southern African Memon Foundation] and the [[Natal Memon Jamaat]].<ref>http://www.memon.com/html/events/fimc/ARMoti.htm</ref>

