{{Infobox language |name=Tamahaq |states=[[Algeria]], [[Libya]], [[Niger]] |region=[[Sahara]] |speakers=77,000 |date=2001 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Berber languages|Berber]] |fam3=[[Tuareg languages|Tuareg]] |fam4=Northern |iso3=thv |glotto=taha1241 |glottorefname=Tahaggart Tamahaq }}
'''Tamahaq''' (''Tahaggart Tamahaq'', ''Tamahaq Tahaggart'') is the only known [[Tuareg languages|Northern Tuareg language]], spoken in [[Algeria]], western [[Libya]] and northern [[Niger]]. It varies little from the Southern Tuareg [[Berber languages]] of the [[Aïr Mountains]], [[Azawagh]] and [[Kel Adagh|Adagh]]. The differences mostly consist of sound substitutions, such as ''Tamahaq'' instead of ''Tamajaq'' or ''Tamasheq''.
==Varieties== There are three main varieties of Tamahaq: *''Tahaggart'', spoken around the [[Ahaggar Mountains]] in southern Algeria by the [[Kel Ahaggar]] confederation *''Ajjer'', spoken by the [[Kel Ajjer]] confederation *''Ghat'', spoken around [[Djanet]] in southeast Algeria and [[Ghat, Libya|Ghat]] in Libya.
According to Blench (2006), Tahaggart and Ghat are distinct Tuareg languages.
